The '''Arapaho language''' or '''Arapaho proper''' (also spelled "Arapahoe"; in Arapaho: '''''Hin<U+00F3>no<U+2019>eit<U+00ED><U+00ED>t''''' {{sfn|Conathan|2006|loc='A'}}) is a one of the [[Plains Algonquian languages]], closely related to [[Gros Ventre language|Gros Ventre]] and other [[Arapahoan languages]]. It is spoken by under 300 people over age 50 in Wyoming, and in Oklahoma by "only a handful of people . . . all near eighty or older".{{sfn|Cowell|Moss|2008|p=1}} As such, it is in danger of becoming [[Language death|extinct]]. As of 1996, there were approximately 1,000 speakers among the Northern Arapaho.{{sfn|Greymorning|2001|p=287}} As of 2008, the authors of a newly published grammar estimated there were slightly over 250 fluent speakers, plus "quite a few near-fluent passive understanders".{{sfn|Cowell|Moss|2008|p=1}} In 2008, it was reported that a school had been opened to teach the language to children.{{sfn|''New York Times''|2008 October 18|p=}}

==Dialects==
Besawunena, only attested from a wordlist collected by Kroeber, differs only slightly from Arapaho, though a few of its sound changes resemble those seen in Gros Ventre. It had speakers among the Northern Arapaho as recently as the late 1920s. 

==Phonology==
Among the sound changes in the evolution from [[Proto-Algonquian language|Proto-Algonquian]] to Arapaho are the loss of Proto-Algonquian '''*k''', followed by '''*p''' becoming either {{IPA|/k/}} or {{IPA|/t<U+0283>/}}; the two Proto-Algonquian [[semivowel]]s merging to either {{IPA|/n/}} or {{IPA|/j/}}; and '''*m''' often becoming {{IPA|/b/}}. Arapaho is unusual among Algonquian languages in retaining the contrast between the reconstructed phonemes '''*r''' and '''*<U+03B8>''' (generally as {{IPA|/n/}} and {{IPA|/<U+03B8>/}}, respectively).{{sfn|Hale|2001|pp=283-284}}{{sfn|Goddard|1974|p=}}{{sfn|Goddard|1990|p=103}} These and other changes serve to give Arapaho a phonological system very divergent from that of Proto-Algonquian and other Algonquian languages, and even from languages spoken in the adjacent [[Great Basin]]. Some examples comparing Arapaho words with their cognates in Proto-Algonquian can illustrate this:{{sfn|Goddard|1974|pp=1974:104, 106, 107, 108}}{{sfn|Goddard|2001|p=75}}{{sfn|Goddard|1990|p=103}}
