===Vowels===
Almost uniquely among the world's languages, it has no [[Open vowel|low vowels]], such as {{IPA|/a/}}. 

At the level of pronunciation, Arapaho words cannot begin with a vowel, so where the underlying form of a word begins with a vowel, a prothetic {{IPA|/h/}} is added.{{sfn|Cowell|Moss|2008|p=14}}

Arapaho has a series of four short vowels {{IPA|/i e o u/}} (pronounced {{IPA|[<U+026A> <U+025B> <U+0254> <U+028A>]}}) and four long vowels {{IPA|/i<U+02D0> e<U+02D0> o<U+02D0> u<U+02D0>/}} (customarily written <U+27E8>ii ee oo uu<U+27E9> and pronounced {{IPA|[i<U+02D0> <U+025B><U+02D0> <U+0254><U+02D0> u<U+02D0>]}}). The difference in length is phonemically distinctive: compare '''h<U+00ED>si<U+2019>''', "tick" with '''h<U+00ED><U+00ED>si<U+2019>''', "day", and '''h<U+00F3>coo''', "steak" with '''h<U+00F3><U+00F3>coo''', "devil".{{sfn|Cowell|Moss|2008|p=14}} {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} are mostly in complementary distribution, as, with very few exceptions, the former does not occur after [[velar consonant]]s, and the latter only occurs after them. {{IPA|/u/}} does have some exceptions as in the free variants '''kok<U+00ED>y''' ~ '''kok<U+00FA>y''', "gun"; '''kookiy<U+00F3>n''' ~ '''kookuy<U+00F3>n''', "for no reason"; and '''b<U+00ED><U+00ED><U+2019>ox<U+00ED>yoo''' ~ '''b<U+00ED><U+00ED><U+2019>ox<U+00FA>yoo''', "Found in the Grass" (a mythological character). There is only one minimal pair to illustrate the contrast in distribution: '''n<U+00FA>hu<U+2019>''', "this" versus '''n<U+00ED>hi<U+2019>-''', "X was done with Y", in which '''n<U+00ED>hi<U+2019>-''' only occurs in bound form.{{sfn|Cowell|Moss|2008|pp=14-16}}

There are four diphthongs, {{IPA|/ei ou oe ie/}}, and several triphthongs, {{IPA|/eii oee ouu/}} as well as extended sequences of vowels such as {{IPA|/eee/}} with stress on either the first or the last vowel in the combination.{{sfn|Salzman ''et al.''|1998|p=}} 

